:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF018959%2F1"><gtr:id>40131185-3891-44CF-AF33-B41500AAC309</gtr:id><gtr:title>Strategies of Ignorance: Mapping the political uses of uncertainty within medicine</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F018959/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;br />&amp;nbsp;During this one-year postdoctoral fellowship, Linsey McGoey will develop the findings of her PhD research, which has examined the uses of ignorance and uncertainty during debates over the safety of selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI) anti-depressant drugs. The findings of her thesis are three-fold: First, she demonstrates that policymakers within the UK?s National Health Service are frustrated with their inability to access clinical trial data necessary for developing treatment guidelines. Second, she suggests that when practitioners and policymakers wish to criticize the socio-political factors that make it difficult to access clinical trial data, their dissent must be limited to the universe of numbers, a phenomena that she terms the ?moral authority of objectivity? in medicine. Third, her thesis suggests government regulators employed a use of ?strategic ignorance? in order to absolve themselves of liability in not disclosing the knowledge of adverse effects when they first learned of them. During her postdoctoral research, she plans to publish article in leading peer-reviewed journals, present papers at UK-based and international conferences, and develop grant proposals for her next large-scale project, initially planned as an analysis of the unintended effects of philanthropic endeavors in the pharmaceutical industry.
